==Orchid　蘭:==
===Orchid in Chinese Painting:===
* Wu Changshuo 吳昌碩 (1844-1927): 雙勾蘭圖軸 (Double Outlined Orchids). Hanging Scroll, 1897, ink on paper, 149.8x40.5cm, Zhejiang Provincial Museum.
> Published in Xiaoneng Yang: Tracing the Past, drawing the future: master ink painters in twentieth-century China. Milan: 5 Continents, 2010: 94-96.
> Other orchids of Wu Changshuo see Joohyun Lee: Wu Changshuo (1844-1927). Der letzte Literatenmaler im modernen China. Berlin: Logos, 2011: 76-81,95-97
* Colophon of the Qianlong emperor to Gu Kaizhi's Admonitions Scroll [[@http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a5/Admonitions_Scroll_Front_End_Panel.jpg|picture]] 
> ====Literature====
* Lothar Ledderose: Das Aroma der Flüsse Yüan und Li. Ein Album mit Orchideenbildern von Chiang Yü-chien. In Roderich  Ptak und Siegfried Englert [Hrsg.]: Ganz Allmählich. Festschrift für Günther Debon. Heidelberg: Heidelberger Verlagsanstalt, 1986
* Yang Li: Mirroring the Wu School: Ma Shouzhen's Orchid Painting. M.A. thesis, University of Alberta (Canada), 2010 [[@http://proquest.umi.com/pqdweb?did=2208243631&sid=3&Fmt=2&clientId=21097&RQT=309&VName=PQD|proquest]] 
===Orchid in Japanese Painting:===
* Nakabayashi Chikutô 中林竹洞: Yûran zu 幽蘭図 (Elegant Orchid). Hanging Scroll, 1827, ink on paper, 143.4x56cm, Terry Welch Collection at Honolulu Academy of Arts.
> Published in Paul Berry and Michiyo Morioka: Literati Modern, bujinga from late Edo to twentieth century Japan, Seattle: University of Washington Press, 2008: 188-189.
* Ike no Taiga 池大雅 (1723-1776): 
> - Keiseki zu 蕙石図 (Orchid and Rock). Hangingscroll,  ~1752, finger painting, ink on paper, 90.3x43.3cm, Taiga Museum, Kyôto. 
> Published in Kobayashi Tadashi, Sasaki Jôhei, Okawa Naomi, Hg. Nihon bijutsu zenshû, dai-19 kan: Taiga to Ôkyo. Edo no kaiga 3 kenchiku 2. Tôkyô: Kôdansha, 1993: no.11; Felice Fischer with Kyoko Kinoshita: Ike Taiga and Tokuyama Gyokuran. Japanese Masters of the Brush. Philadelphia Museum of Art, 2007: no. 21.
> - Orchids with Calligraphy. Finger painting, ink on silk, hanging scroll, 45.4x60.5cm, Sansô Collection
> Published in Felice Fischer with Kyoko Kinoshita: Ike Taiga and Tokuyama Gyokuran. Japanese Masters of the Brush. Philadelphia Museum of Art, 2007: no. 20.
> - Book of Tang Poetry in Five Calligraphic Styles. Ink on paper, folding book, 27.5x10.6cm each page, Umezawa Memorial Gallery, Tokyo.
> Published in Felice Fischer with Kyoko Kinoshita: Ike Taiga and Tokuyama Gyokuran. Japanese Masters of the Brush. Philadelphia Museum of Art, 2007: no. 75.
> - Orchids in a Vase. Ink on paper, hanging scroll, 119.8x41.5cm, Gitter-Yelen Collection, New Orleans.
> Published in Felice Fischer with Kyoko Kinoshita: Ike Taiga and Tokuyama Gyokuran. Japanese Masters of the Brush. Philadelphia Museum of Art, 2007: no. 201.
* Tokuyama Gyokuran: Orchids with a Japanese Poem by Gyokuran. Ink and color on paper, part of a pair of hanging scrolls with a Plum Blossom painting by Taiga, 17.1x51.1cm, Tokyo National Museum.
> Published in Felice Fischer with Kyoko Kinoshita: Ike Taiga and Tokuyama Gyokuran. Japanese Masters of the Brush. Philadelphia Museum of Art, 2007: no. 98.


* Ôtsuki Bankei (1801-1878): Orchids. Hand Scroll, ink on linen, 35.4x47.8cm.
> Published in Stephen Addiss: Japanese Quest for a New Vision. The Impact of Visiting Chinese Painters, 1600-1900. Selections from the Hutchinson Collection. Kansas University, Spencer Museum of Art, 1986: 64-65
> ====Literature====
* Nakamura Tanio: Orchids, Bamboo and Stones by Tesshu Tokusai, Kobijutsu 古美術40 (March 1973): 69-
* 星山 晋也: 玉畹の隠逸と墨蘭, 早稲田大学大学院文学研究科紀要 文学・芸術学編 (37), p133-144, 1991  
* [[@http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/b/bokuran.htm|JAANUS / bokuran 墨蘭]]  
===Orchid in Korean Painting:===
* Yi Ha-Eung (1820-1898): Orchids. Joseon Dynasty, 1878, Ink on Silk, Ten-fold Standing Screen, 163.5x32.5cm a strip. 
> Published in "Fascination". Dhan Ho Mun Hwa Yon Gu, No. 13 (2010): 81-85, 160-165.
* Orchids of Min Yôngik 閔泳翊（1869—1914）and Kim Yongjin 金容鎮 (1878-1968) in the style of Wu Changshuo 吳昌碩 (1844-1927).
> Joohyun Lee: Wu Changshuo (1844-1927). Der letzte Literatenmaler im modernen China. Berlin: Logos, 2011: 197-206
